{{Infobox treaty | name = Working Conditions (Hotels and Restaurants) Convention, 1991 | long_name = Convention concerning Working Conditions in Hotels, Restaurants and similar Establishments | image = Working Conditions (Hotels and Restaurants).svg | image_width = 325 | caption = Parties to the convention | type = | date_drafted = | date_signed = {{start date and age|1991|6|25|df=yes|paren=yes}} | location_signed = [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]] | date_sealed = | date_effective = 7 July 1994 | condition_effective = Two ratifications | date_expiration = | signatories = | parties = | ratifiers = Sixteen | depositor = Director-General of the [[International Labour Office]] | language = | languages = French and English | wikisource = }}
The '''Working Conditions (Hotels and Restaurants) Convention, 1991''', officially the '''Convention concerning Working Conditions in Hotels, Restaurants and similar Establishments''' is an [[International Labour Organization#International Labour Conference|International Labour Organization Convention]] adopted in 1991 during the 78 International Labour Conference.
It sets standards for work in hotels and restaurants. According to the convention, workers have a right to "reasonable normal hours of work" and "minimum daily and weekly rest periods", compensation (in time or remuneration) of work on holidays. Furthermore a basic remuneration should be paid in regular intervals, regardless of tips.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/normlex/en/f?p=1000:12100:0::NO:12100:P12100_INSTRUMENT_ID:312317|title=C172 - Working Conditions (Hotels and Restaurants) Convention, 1991 (No. 172)|work=ILO|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref>
== Ratifications== As of September 2012, 16 countries were party to the convention: Austria, Barbados, Cyprus, Dominican Republic, Fiji, Germany, Guyana, Iraq, Ireland, Lebanon, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands (for Curaçao, Sint Maarten and the Caribbean Netherlands),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minbuza.nl/en/key-topics/treaties/search-the-treaty-database/1991/6/005092.html|title=Convention concerning Working Conditions in Hotels, Restaurants and similar Establishments|accessdate=20 September 2012|work=Kingdom of the Netherlands (Treaty database)}}</ref> Spain, Switzerland and Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/normlex/en/f?p=1000:11300:0::NO:11300:P11300_INSTRUMENT_ID:312317|title=Ratifications of C172 - Working Conditions (Hotels and Restaurants) Convention, 1991 (No. 172)|work=ILO|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> {{clear}}
